04447nam a22004935i 9780773561526DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19901990xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735615267 a10.1515/97807735615262doi  a(DE-B1597)657551  a(OCoLC)1394872396  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aEDU0160002bisacsh04a370/.942/09021 aMiner, John N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGrammar Schools of Medieval England :bA.F. Leach in Historiographical Perspective /cJohn N. Miner. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1990] 4c©1990  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface -- tIllustrations -- tThe Contribution of A.F. Leach -- tIntroductory Survey -- tBackground to the Endowed Schools Act of 1869 -- tLeach as Assistant Charity Commissioner -- tAnalysis of "English Schools at the Reformation, 1546—48" and "The Schools of Medieval England" -- tThe Secular Origins of England's Schools -- tThe Strengths and Weaknesses of Leach's Research -- tThe Grammar Program -- tThe Grammar Program -- tEducational Institutions -- tLeach in Historicgraphical Context: Contemporary Criticism and Recent Scholarship -- tConclusion -- tAppendices -- tCharity Commission Report (in manuscript) on Chichester, 27 July 1886, by A.F. Leach -- tLatin Grammar -- tDictamen -- tSpeculative Grammar -- tWilliam Chartham’s Speculum Parvulorum -- tEducational Documents -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLeach struggled to rid his countrymen of the persistent myth that the monks had been the schoolmasters of the pre-Reformation period in England. To accomplish his goal he embarked on a program of research and publication, based on a mass of hitherto unexplored documents, to establish the great antiquity of many of the nation's Latin schools and to show that they derived from clerical, but secular, colleges of Anglo-Saxon times. Showing this would, he hoped, eliminate the persistant belief that monks had been the school-masters of pre-Reformation England. Miner argues that previous readings of Leach, which suggest that his main concern is to take issue with the Reformation and argue that this great watershed in history was - at least with regard to education - a retrograde step rather than a great movement forward, have not taken into account the full range of his publications. The aim of the present study is thus to place both Leach's achievements and his more controversial theses in historical context. A separate chapter devoted to unpublished material from the Charity Commission reveals Leach's method of work and provides an analytic survey of opinions on his work by reviewers and historians. The author supplements Leach's lack of material on the school curriculum through descriptive analysis of grammatical manuscripts from the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries, showing the presence of an educational Christendom of which Leach was clearly unaware.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356152640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773561526423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773561526/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles